text.tspan: CourseRatingS -
Ryan Drapeau, Emily Gu, Vimala Jampala
Better performance with querying and
loading of the database into the browser.
One of the most stressful times during the school
year for a student is registration for the next quarter.
Picking the best classes and more importantly the
teacher for the class could change a studentâ€™s
experience for the course. At the end of each quarter,
students fill out an evaluation form for professors
and the course as a whole. Currently, UW provides a
Course Evaluation Catalog (CEC) for students to visit
in order to see how students have rated a course.
The layout is simply a list of evaluations (1 for each
course), which makes it quite difficult to compare
ratings. The site does not directly elicit any average
or aggregate information about courses or professors
over time. The catalog does not have any search
capability causing users to resort to the browser's
find functionality, which can yield bad results.
CourseRatings is built around 3 core features: search,
table visualization, and D3 plots. The search is
implemented as 3 searchable drop-down menus,
which then computes an intersection of the selection.
These data are then passed to a table where the
courses / professors are displayed as rows with their
values as the columns. Color is used to convey good
(green), okay (yellow), and bad (red) scores to the user.
Problem
& Motivation
Approach & Results
The underlying motivation for this project was the
desire to have a tool that would be useful to students
and instructors alike to look at evaluations. Our
application reveals deeper insights and user-friendly
visualizations that would be useful when deciding
what course to take or which instructor to take a
course from.
D3 provides excellent mechanisms for displaying
entries over the quarters. These plots are used on
the Course detail and the Instructor detail page. D3 is
also used in the Course Comparison page (see below).
Course Comparison page allows users to see the
difference in ratings between various courses.
In addition to the Course and Instructor detail
pages, there is also a Department page that
displays all of the courses in the department.
The Top Courses and Instructors are shown
above the table. These are computed using a
linear combination of the average Overall rating
and the number of entries in the selection.
Similar entries (the same class over several
quarters) are collapsed into a single row that
averages each value. The user can click an arrow
on the side of the row to expand it to show all
entries within. Each instructor and course code
may be clicked on to enter the specifc detailed
page for that entry.
Continue to scrape CEC to gather more data
on courses and professors in the future.
More integration with the Course Catalog
(currently offered / offered next quarter).
